<p>
When we graph the points <m>(\theta,\sin(\theta))</m> we get the <q>sine
wave.</q> This follows from the fact that on a unit circle the radian
measure of a central angle, <m>\theta</m>, is equal to the length of the
arc it cuts. So we get the <q>sine wave</q> when we roll the arc length
out as a straight line on the <m>x</m>-axis.
</p>
<image source="images/SineGraph2.png" width="100%" />
