<subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONmodel-with-trig"> <!-- bad -->
<title>Modeling with Trigonometric Functions </title>

<p>
  The sine and cosine functions are <term>periodic</term>
  functions. As such they are useful for modeling phenomena which are
  cyclical in nature; that is, phenomena which repeat the same pattern
  periodically.  This periodicity is reflected in the formulas:

  <md>
    <mrow>
      \cdots = \sin(\theta-2\pi)\amp  =\sin(\theta)=\sin(\theta+2\pi)=\sin(\theta+4\pi)=\cdots 
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
      \cdots = \cos(\theta-2\pi)\amp=\cos(\theta)=\cos(\theta+2\pi)=\cos(\theta+4\pi)=\cdots
    </mrow>
  </md>
 

  The rationale for the term <term>periodic</term> is
  very evident when we graph <m>\sin(\theta)</m> on a set of
  <m>(\theta, y)</m> axes.
</p>
<image source="images/Periodicity1.png" width="95%" />
<!--  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1.3In,width=5in]{../Figures/Periodicity1}} -->
<p>
As you can see a full cycle is completed over every interval of length
<m>2\pi</m>. Thus the sine and cosine functions are said to be
<m>2\pi</m>-periodic. We can start our cycle for any value of <m>\theta</m>, but
you are probably accustomed to graphing one complete cycle over the
interval <m>[0,2\pi]</m> as in the graphs below.
</p>
<exercise xml:id="DRILLPeriodicFunctions">
<statement>
<p>
  Because <m>\sin(t)</m> and <m>\cos(t)</m> complete one cycle on an interval of
  <m>2\pi</m> they are called <m>2\pi</m>-<term>periodic</term> functions. Suppose
  that <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> are constants. Choose several non-zero values
  for <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> (at least three of each) and graph the
  function
  <me>z(t)=A \sin(t) + B\cos(t)+C</me> to show graphically that
  <m>z(t)</m> is also a <m>2\pi</m>-periodic function.
</p>
</statement>
</exercise>

<!-- <figure> -->
<!-- <caption> -->
<!-- <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Hertz_Heinrich/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Hertz_Heinrich/">This figure needs a caption.</url> -->
<!-- </caption> -->
<image source="images/Periodicity2.png" width="40%"/>
<!-- </figure> -->
