<subsection xml:id="SECTIONpolar-coordinates">
<title>Polar Coordinates</title>

<p>

When we say that the coordinates of point <m>P</m> in the plane are
<m>(x,y)</m> we are referring to the <term>Cartesian (or rectangular)
coordinates</term>. They are named in honor of Ren√© Descartes who, as
we mentioned in <xref ref="SECTIONroberv-conic-sect">Section</xref>,
was one of the pioneers in applying algebra to geometry. The geometric
picture that goes with this is shown below.
</p>

<!-- <figure> -->
<!-- <caption> -->
<!-- <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Curves/Spiral/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Curves/Spiral/">This figure needs a caption.</url> -->
<!-- </caption> -->
<image source="images/CartCoord3.png" width="40%"/>
<!-- </figure> -->
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[6]{l}{1.6in} -->
<!--   \vskip-6mm  \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!--   \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1in,width=1.5in]{../Figures/CartCoord3}} -->
<!--   \label{fig:CartCoord} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->

<p>
Using rectangular coordinates is one way to to translate geometry
problems into algebra problems and <foreign>vice versa</foreign>. This simple
idea changed forever how mathematics is done. Really.
</p>

<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[6]{r}{1.6in} -->
<!--   \vskip-3mm  -->
<!--   \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!--   \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1in,width=1.5in]{../Figures/CartCoord4}} -->
<!--   \label{fig:CartCoord2} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->
<p>

But Cartesian coordinates are not the only way we can locate points in
the plane.  If we superimpose a right triangle on the diagram above,
as shown at the left, we can find another way to locate <m>P</m>. Since <m>P</m>
is the endpoint of the ray starting at the origin and ending at <m>P</m>
the ordered pair of numbers <m>(r,\theta)</m> works just as well as the
ordered pair <m>(x,y)</m>. The numbers <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m> are called the
<term>polar coordinates</term> of <m>P</m>.
</p>
<!-- <figure> -->
<!-- <caption> -->
<!-- <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Curves/Spiral/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Curves/Spiral/">This figure needs a caption.</url> -->
<!-- </caption> -->
<image source="images/CartCoord4.png" width="60%"/>
<!-- </figure> -->


<p>
There are advantages and disadvantages to either coordinate
system. For example the coordinates in the Cartesian system are
unique. There is only point with rectangular coordinates, <m>(3,4)</m>
(where <m>x=3</m> and <m>y=4</m>). This is not true of polar coordinates. The
point with polar coordinates <m>(2, \pi)</m> (where <m>r=2</m> and <m>\theta=\pi</m>)
is the same as the point with polar coordinates <m>(2,-\pi)</m> (where
<m>r=2</m> and <m>\theta=-\pi</m>).
It is also the same as the point with polar coordinates <m>(-2,\pi)</m>,
where <m>r=-2</m> (gasp!). The idea of a negative value for <m>r</m> is a
little jarring because we usually think of the negative sign as
denoting negative numbers. Instead, think of it as meaning <q>go
the opposite direction.</q>
</p>

<aside>
<title>Comment</title>
<p>
Thinking this way also explains why the
  negative of a negative must be positive. The number <m>2</m> is at the
  endpoint of a ray pointing to the right along the <m>x</m>-axis.
  If we put a negative  sign in front we <q>go the opposite direction</q>
  to <m>-2</m>. Another
  negative will reverse the direction again.
</p>
</aside>


