<subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONCircularMotion">
<title>Circular Motion</title>
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[11]{l}{1.9in} -->
<!--   \vskip-4mm  \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!--   \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1.7in,width=1.9in]{../Figures/DiffSinCos3}} -->
<!--   \label{fig:DiffSinCos3} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->
<p>
Recall that when a central angle <m>\theta</m>, of a unit circle is
measured in radians then the arclength subtended by that angle will
also be <m>\theta</m> as seen in the sketch at the left. Similarly, when
we increase the angle <m>\theta</m> by <m>\dx{\theta}</m> the blue arc is also
of length <m>\dx{\theta}</m>. Moreover,  by the Principle
of Local Linearity the blue arc length can be thought of as an
infinitely small straight line. Thus it is the hypotenuse of the blue
triangle.
</p>
<figure  xml:id="FIGURESinDeriv">
<caption>
</caption>
<image source="images/DiffSinCos3.png" width="40%"/>
</figure>

<p>
Notice that when <m>\theta</m> is increased by <m>\dx{\theta}</m>, <m>y</m> is
increased by <m>\dx{y}</m>, but <m>x</m> is decreased by <m>\dx{x}</m> which
makes <m>\dx{x}</m> negative.  But the sides of a triangle must be positive
so the label on the blue triangle is <m>-\dx{x}</m>.
</p>

<exercise>
<p>
Referring to <xref ref="FIGURESinDeriv"></xref>,
<ol cols="3" marker="i">
<li>
<p>
     Show that 
<m> AB=\sin(\theta)</m> 
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
Show that <m> OA=\cos(\theta)</m>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>
Show that
<m> \triangle OAB</m>  and <m>\triangle BCD</m>
      are similar.
    </p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</exercise>

<p>
The relevant portion of <xref ref="FIGURESinDeriv"></xref> are the two similar
triangles shown in  the diagram below.
</p>
<!-- <figure> -->
<!-- <caption> -->
<!-- <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/HistTopics/Brachistochrone/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/HistTopics/Brachistochrone/">This figure needs a caption.</url> -->
<!-- </caption> -->
<image source="images/DiffSinCos4.png" width="40%"/>
<!-- </figure> -->
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[]{r}{2in} -->
<!--   \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!--   \vskip-8mm  -->
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=2in,width=2in]{../Figures/DiffSinCos4}} -->
<!-- \label{fig:DiffSinCos4} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->

<p>
Using the two similar triangles we have
<md> 
<mrow>\dfdx{(\sin(\theta))}{\theta}=\frac{\cos(\theta)}{1}, \amp{}\amp{}\text{ and }\amp{}\amp{}
-\dfdx{(\cos(\theta))}{\theta}=\frac{\sin(\theta)}{1}.</mrow>
</md>
And so we have the following Differentiation Rules. Memorize them.
<dl>
<li>
<title>Derivative of Sine:</title>
<p>
<m>\dx{(\sin(\theta))} = \cos(\theta)\dx{{\theta}}</m>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title>Derivative of Cosine:</title>
<p>
<m>
\dx{(\cos(\theta))}=-\sin(\theta)\dx{\theta}.
</m>
</p>
</li>
</dl>
</p>

<example xml:id="EXAMPLETrigDerivExamples">
<introduction>
<p>
  <!-- \label{TrigDerivExamples} -->
