What is <m>\omega</m> in <xref
  ref="EQUATIONSHO2">Equation</xref>?
</p>
</hint>
</exercise>

<paragraphs  xml:id="DIGRESSIONNeglGrav">
<title>DIGRESSION: Neglecting Gravity </title>
<p>
  You may be wondering why we<rsq/>ve consistently neglected the force due to gravity
  (which will be the weight of the object or <m>mg</m> where <m>m</m> is it<rsq/>s
  mass and <m>g=9.8 \frac{\text{meters}}{\text{second}^2}</m>) in
  <xref ref="EQUATIONSHO2">equation</xref>). Actually, this was accounted for when we
  chose our coordinate system so that <m>y=0</m> at the equilibrium
  point. At equilibrium the upward force from the spring exactly
  balances the downward force of gravity (that<rsq/>s why it's called
  equilibrium) so we can proceed as if those forces are not
  there. This does not say that there are no other forces acting on
  the object, only that such forces as exist are exactly in balance;
  they add to zero.
</p>

<p>

  If you buy this intuitive argument, then fine. If not, work through
  the following problem.
</p>
<p>

</p>

