<!--   \label{fig:arcsin6} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->

<p>
From the sketch we see that if we restrict the range of
<m>\inverse\sin(x)</m> to the interval <m>[-\pi/2, \pi/2]</m> the graph of
<m>\inverse\sin(x)</m> (in blue) will always\aside{Except at the
  endpoints of course. What do you think the slope of
  <m>\inverse\sin(x)</m> is at <m>x=\frac{\pi}{2}</m>? have a positive slope,
and therefore a positive derivative.
</p>
<p>

With this restriction in place we define the derivative of the
inverse sine as follows.
</p>


<definition xml:id="DEFINITIONInvSin">
<title>The Derivative of the Inverse Sine</title>
<statement>
<p>
  <!-- \label{def:InvSin} -->
  The derivative of the inverse sine function is defined to be,
  <me>\displaystyle\dfdx{(\inverse\sin(x)}{x}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}</me>,
  where <m>-\frac{\pi}{2}\lt \inverse\sin(x)\lt \frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  What function is <m>\inverse\sin(x)</m>, as defined in
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONInvSin">Definition</xref> the inverse off?
</p>
</statement>
<hint>
<p>
Naturally, <m>\inverse\sin(x)</m> is the inverse of <m>\sin(x)</m>, but
    with which domain?
</p>
</hint>
</problem>
<p>
Similarly, if we restrict the range of <m>\inverse\cos(x)</m> to
<m>0\lt x \lt\pi</m> its derivative will always be negative.
</p>

<definition xml:id="DEFINITIONInvCos">
<title>The Derivative of the Inverse Cosine</title>
<statement>
<p>
  <!-- \label{def:InvCos} -->
  The derivative of the inverse sine function is defined to be,
  <m>\displaystyle\dfdx{(\inverse\cos(x))}{x}=\frac{-1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}</m>,
  where <m>0\lt x\lt \pi</m>.
      
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

